  Discussion    For years sucrose has been used as communal table sugar. However its high production costs and hostile effects on health have amplified the need of finding a replacement for sucrose. A new sweetener Thaumatin is discovered, likely be 2000 times sweeter than sucrose but remain unused because of its unpleasant flavor (Hanover &amp; White, 1993). It is not expensive to convert glucose into fructose by the help of xylose isomerase. Xylose isomerase is the enzyme which is being used for isomerization of glucose into fructose. This research work focuses on glucose isomerization production from a locally isolated strain of  Escherichia coli . The study showed raw xylose isomerase was thermostable and exhibited optimum value from  E. coli  at 85&deg;C temperature and pH 8 (Table 4.11 and 4.13). In accordance to the previous studies the competant production of xylose isomerase produced by  Actinoplanes missouriensis  is 25 U/ml at 75&deg;C and at 7.0 pH and the stated production of xylose isomerase is 10 U/min/ml in  Bacillus licheniformis  at 70&deg;C.  Lactobacillus brevis  formed the highest production of enzyme. The enzyme was reported dynamic at low pH but unstable at high temperature and hence was not suitable for economic mistreatment. (Bhosale  et al .,1996). Therefore neutral conditions are suitable for the best activity of this enzyme, which capacitate it to work at low pH, as acid is mostly required for the washing of substrate. Suitably high temperature is needed for the fructose conversion (Fatima &amp; Hussain, 2015). While performing studies of optimized fermentation, it was conceived that high yield of raw enzyme was detected when amount of yeast extract and peptone was amplified. The highest yield was observed in flask no. 2 while doing fermentation for second turn which has 2.5% yeast extract and 0.5% peptone and 1% NaCl (Table 4.5). However in earlier studies it has been stated cultivation media for  E. coli  should have balanced salt concentration since greater salt concentrations is a cause of inhibition of the cell growth (Riesenberg  et al.,  1990). The nitrogen component of media should be in a narrowing range as it has a negative impact on growth of cells (Thompson  et al ., 1985). The optimum temperature for finest cell growth was also detected by incubating the flasks of raw and treated enzyme at two different temperatures i.e. 30&deg;C and 37&deg;C. The optimal temperature for fermentation was found to be 37&deg;C (Table 4.8). The optimal temperature reported for  E. coli  growth is between 30&deg;C and 38&deg;C (Andersson  et al.,  1996). The partial characterization of raw enzyme was executed to optimize the physical conditions for best conversion of glucose into fructose. The enzyme activity relative to amount of fructose produced, was quantified by the method of (Schenk and Bisswanger 1998). Strongly acidic conditions are required in which fructose forms a red complex with resorcinol and FeNH4(SO4)2 .The optical densities of the reaction mixtures are measured to calculate amount of fructose. (Schenk &amp; Bisswanger, 1998). The xylose isomerase activity was raised upto 10.6 U/ml at 75&ordm;C after which the activity started decreasing. The maximum activity was shown at 85&deg;C was 10.6 U/ml for  E. coli . The decrease in activity may be due to its heat stability at specific incubation temperatures (Table 4.11). The prior studies showed that enzymes from different microorganisms have different optimum incubation temperatures. Most of the marketable preparations of XI have a temperature optimum of 60&deg;C to 65&deg;C. The thermal inactivation weakened the enzyme activity and exerted limitation on the operating time of the incubator (Volkin &amp; Klibanov, 1989). Therefore enzyme xylose isomerase has an extraordinary Heat stability. Enzyme from  E. coli  has an optimum temperature of 85&deg;C which makes it more practicable for commercial use. Increase in the amount of enzyme was caused by increase in activity. The peak value of activity is obtained at 950 &micro;l of 100 mM of glucose used. Further increase had no reasonable increase in the activity (Table 4.12). It was judged by deductions that these results are due to specific activity (U/ml/min) of the enzyme which is not increasing. Commercial application of GI demands an acidic pH optimum to enable Starch liquefaction and glucose isomerization require acidic Ph. Neutral pH is required for optimum production of enzyme as shown in (Table 4.13). Studies revealed the pH is changed by mutagenesis for example, conserved residue of Glu-186 were located, close to the active site of xylose Isomerase produced by  A. missouriensis  but does not contribute in the substrate or metal ion binding. The negative charge from this group  was excluded by its mutation to glutamine, which caused the dropping its pH optimum to 6.25 (Tilbeurgh  et al ., 1992). The effect of cobalt ion on raw enzyme activity was also analyzed and the outcome showed increase in activity in the presence of Co+2 ions (Table 4.14). Since the use of Co+2 is a threat to human health and cause environment pollution. It was detected that some organisms like  Arthrobacter  sp. and Streptomyces olivaceus furthermore mutants of  Streptomyces olivochromogenes  do not require cobalt for optimum production of xylose isomerase (Raynolds, 1973). As shown in Figure 13, the purified enzyme showed peak relative activity at 85&ordm;C and was still relatively active at 90&ordm;C. It was detected to be stable at temperatures up to 85&ordm;C and it maintained about 60% of its activity at 90&ordm;C. The xylose isomerase showed thermostable properties different from those of other thermostable microorganisms including  Thermoanaero bacterium  strain JW/SL-YS 489 (Liu  et al.,  1996),  Bacillus thermoantarticus  (Lama  et al ., 2001),  E. coli  K12 (Rozanov  et al.,  2009) and  Thermus thermophilus  (Xu  et al ., 2009); therefore, concluding that it is a thermostable enzyme. It&rsquo;s ideal pH is 7.0, and it is stable crossways a broad pH ranging from 5.5 to 8.5 as shown in (figure 17 and 18). Wherease, its  K m value was detected to be 681.48 mM; higher than those of  Bacillus  sp. Tx-3 ( K m value of 100 mM correspondingly). Comparatively its Vmax value (74.074 &micro;M/min/mg) is lower than bacillus sp. Tx-3 (Vmax value of 28.6 &mu;M/min/mg) correspondingly) (Kitada  et al ., 1989). It has been reported previously by scientists that glucose isomerases usually require divalent metal ions such as Mg+2, Co+2 or Mn+2 as cofactors but results were different from (Lama  et al. , 2001, Lehmacher &amp; Bisswangher 1990). The effect of metal ions of xylose isomerase from locally isolated  E.coli  was detected to be similar to the effects of enzyme from  Bacillus thermoantarcticus    (Lama  et al. , 2001). The results of values obtained from two different bacterias were different showing dissimilar effects. The molecular mass of the enzyme was estimated by SDS-PAGE as 43.5 kDa (Figure 4.9). This value is somewhat different from those of the xylose isomerases  from  Streptomyces  sp. EC10 (molecular mass of 42 kDa) (Belfaquih &amp; Peninckx 2000) and from  Streptomyces  sp. SK strain (molecular mass of 43-kDa) (Borgi  et al  2004)   Conclusion    The xylose isomerase works efficiently to isomerize glucose into fructose at lower pH and high temperature. There is a wide range within which the enzyme is thermostable. Similarly there exist wide ranges of pH within which the enzyme shows stability. The presence of cobalt, magnesium, manganese and calcium ions resulted in increase in enzyme activity. The cobalt ion act as cofactor and enormously enhances the activity of enzyme. It indicates that enzyme xylose isomerase exhibit peak activity at pH of 8.0. At the end we can conclude that the gene of this enzyme if cloned and overexpressed can be used for the production of HFCS 
