 ABSTRACT., 
  Xylose isomerase was competently found to be produced by locally isolated E.coli. When it was grown in medium containing 1% xylose as a carbon source this strain produced a raw xylose isomerase activity of roughly 1.85 mg of total protein. Peak enzymatic activity was 53.75 U/ml as detected by nutrient broth components having 1 % NaCl, 0.5% peptone and 2.5 % yeast extract correspondingly. The enzyme was purified after optimization by ammonium sulphate precipitation, dialysis and SDS-PAGE. The approximate molecular weight of xylose isomerase from locally isolated E.coli is 43.5 kDa as determined by SDS-PAGE. The Km value estimated for xylose isomerase is 681.48 mM and its Vmax value is recorded as 74.04 (U/ml/min). The purified enzyme has optimum activity at 80&deg;C and pH 7.0. It is stable at pH 5.5&ndash;8.5 and at temperatures up to 85&deg;C. These findings designate that xylose isomerase has the capacity for commercial application, chiefly for (HFCS) high-fructose corn syrup production by Escherichia   coli. INTRODUCTION   The xylose isomerase is classified as belonging to class of isomerase having E.C. 5.3.1.5. An essential role of xylose isomerase is the conversion of xylose and glucose into xylulose and fructose, respectively. It was revealed by studies, that the most important enzyme produced in bulk till now is xylose isomerase (Fatima &amp; Hussain, 2015). After which comes, the amylase and then protease. The product of isomerization i.e. Xylulose is needed for nutrition of saprophytic bacteria. These bacteria are dependent on decaying plants for their food and are also responsible for bioconversion of hemicellulose into ethanol. Figure 1.1. Mechanism of Glucose isomerase reaction a) in vitro reaction b)   in vivo reaction (adopted from Fatima and Hussain, 2015 
 &nbsp; 
 &nbsp; 
  Its catalytic conversion to fructose helps in the formation of High Fructose Corn Syrup (HFCS) (Brown  et al.,  1993). For this reason, it is also known as glucose isomerase (Jensen &amp; Rugh, 1987). Mainly it is extracted from corn which is the reason by which it got its name. It has the composition of glucose and fructose in 1:1. It is readily very sweet that&rsquo;s why it is used in industries for the synthesis of food and beverages. But at the same time its excessive use give rise to obesity in male and female. Sucrose obtained from sugar beet (40%), and sugar cane (60%) was utilized in world till 1976. The usage of HFCS was first introduced in Japan and then in United States. This was succeeded just because of unavailability of sucrose after the Cuban revolution in 1958. And till now it is the most important enzyme profitably used in industries. Glucose is cheaper thus its conversion to fructose by a catalyst xylose isomerase is economical. Since, the catalytic conversion causes the isomerization of two compounds of xylose and glucose. Xylose isomerase act as a catalyst in the isomerization of xylose to xylulose (Jefferies &amp; Shi, 1999). The history of enzyme revealed that xylose isomerase was initially developed by (Marshall &amp; Kooi, 1957) produced by  Pseudomonas hydrophila . The affinity of xylose isomerase was 160 times lesser for glucose as compared to xylose. The specific inducer for the xylose isomerse activity in the growth medium is xylose and the enzyme activity is boosted by the presence of arsenate with xylose. Later on, the xylose isomerase was isolated from  Escherichia intermedia . In this case enzyme was not dependent on xylose but on arsenate. After which the enzyme was extracted from  Bacillus megaterium . Furthermore the enzyme xylose isomerase was isolated from  Paracolobacterium aerogenoids . The sugar from starch of corn was being preferred till now which capacitate the need for the production of HFCS by xylose isomerase (Raadt  et al. , 1994). The previous studies of xylose isomerases indicated that the production of high fructose corn syrup was started in 1864. In 1950s, Clinton wanted to transform glucose from corn starch into fructose with the help of xylose isomerase but it was not implemented. Later on from 1965-1970, Yoshiyuki Takasaki at Japan Institute of Science and Technology introduced xylose isomerase from yeast. After certain years created a joint venture with a Clinton company to make this process lucrative. In this process, corn starch is extracted from corn (maize) by an acid enzyme process. In which carbohydrates are initially broken up and mixed with the enzymes to metabolize and transform into fructose. Alpha amylase is the enzyme which breaks the long chain and then glucoamylase is used to remove the protein. After that activated carbon and demineralization process also occurs. Immobilized xylose isomerase turn the sugar to 52% glucose and 42% fructose and again purify it with carbon. The process of liquid chromatography is used to convert it into HFCS 90. The microbial fermentation process is utilized to form the enzymes (Raadt  et al ., 1994). High fructose corn syrup is profitable for industrial use (Chen, 1980). Xylose isomerase is widely used for the assembly of xylose-fructose syrup (a natural sugar replacement in dietetic products, prophylactic food additives and clinical nutrition products). It has been noticed that the growing demand for sweetners production forced the scientists to refine the technologies. There is a high profile search going on for getting sweeteners by productive and technologically feasible producer strains (Bhosale  et al ., 1996). In these days, the industrialization isomerization process is executed at temperature ranging from 50&ordm;C to 60&ordm;C which yields 40-42% fructose syrup. A further chromatography step is needed to make the yield 55%. Sucrose is less sweetened as compared to HFCS. In the industries the production of HFCS is limited to isomerization on temperature range 90 to 95&ordm;C having 55% fructose by leaving the last chromatography step. It is the most obvious enzyme for the use in studying structurefunction relationship from an academic perspective (Ertunga  et al ., 2007). The enteric bacteria is involved in xylose consumption and four proteins are engaged in it namely xylose permease, xylulokinase, xylose isomerase and a certain regulatory protein. Growth medium has the xylose which by the action of these protein is shifted into the cell and transformed into xylulose. Afterwards catabolism of xylulose occurs with the cooperation of pentose- phosphate pathway which is further converted to xylulose 5 phosphate .  (Schellenberg  et al ., 1983). Xylose isomerase can be obtained from plants, animals, fungi, agricultural residues and microbes. In plants xylose isomerase is responsible for the transformation of xylose to xylulose (Pubol &amp; Exelrod, 1959). Plant&rsquo;s xylose isomerases include plant tissues and wheat germ. It was deduced that the product of transformation in plants is xylulose-5-phosphate as obtained by pentose phosphate pathway. Xylose isomerase is also produced from Agricultural residues like xylan, cornhusk, and hardwood. Nowadays, the fossil fuel is substituted with ethanol which is produced by agricultural residues of hemicellulosic hydrolysates. It is extracted from the species of  Saccharomyces cerevisiae  by the action of xylose isomerase (Mabee, 2007). The role of xylose isomerase is to transform the xylose to xylulose which is fermented into ethanol by the support of pentose phosphate pathway (Maris  et al ., 2006). In these days the need for biofuel type i.e. ethanol is accelerated (Bangrak  et al.,    2011, Mohammadi  et al ., 2011, Tao  et al.,  2011). Xylose isomerase has the capacity to ferment the xylose rich biomass waste to ethanol (Wang  et al ., 1980, Jafferies &amp; Shi 1999). It has been noticed that the xylose isomerase is needed for the production of biofuel ethanol in industries (Faiz  et al.,  2011). The most important sources of xylose isomerases are the microorganisms that are produced by fermentation of bacteria. At first xylose isomerase was reported from  E.coli  (David &amp; Weismeyer, 1970). Microbial xylose isomerases are easy to produce and cost of production is low. Most stable form of xylose isomerases is microbial xylose isomerases which are more stable when compared to the enzymes extracted from animal and plants. The enzymes produced by microorganisms are reported as follows from  Bacillus coagulans, Thermotoga maritima, Thermotoga neapolitana,     Bacillus subtilis, Ampullariella spp, Actinoplan es  missouriensis, Streptomyces     rubuginosus, Streptomyces violaceoniger, Lactobacillus brevis, Lactos pentosus,     Thermoanaerobacterium thermosulfurogenes 4B, Staphyloccocus xylosus, Eschirichia     coli, sea squirt, Ciona intestinalis  (Wong  et al.,  1991; Saari  et al  1987; Drocourt  et al.,    1988; Wilhelm &amp; Hollenberg 1985; Lokman  et al., 1991; Sizemore  et al.,  1991; Schellenberg  et al.,  1983). Xylose isomerase is precisely suitable for the alpha anomer of xylose. The proton replacement occurs between the enzyme xylose isomerase and the substrate xylose by the negation of water substitution step. Only one residue is reported to intervene the movement in xylose isomerase (Schellenberg  et al ., 1983). Two different domains are founded in xylose isomerase: an N-terminal catalytic domain and a C-terminal auxiliary domain. The catalytic crystallized domain of xylose isomerase have a tertiary structure which revealed its architecture. It has been noted that architecture exhibited its globular fold including an eight stranded &alpha;/&beta; barrel. A loop containing an interrelated helices caused the formation of the C-terminal domain which combine with the N-terminal domain of other subunit. It has been observed that the structure of xylose isomerase contain dimers and tetramers that execute biological activity (Bhosale  et al ., 1996). It has been concluded from the data provided that His-271 residues may execute a catalytic role in the xylose isomerase. Each residue is vital for activity and is further chosen for site directed mutagenesis. It has been observed in experiment&rsquo;s result no measurable activity recorded for mutations by change of position of His-271. Whereas by substituting His-271 null activity was determined. It was observed by circular dichroism values that no change is contributed by mutant enzyme structures. The mutant enzyme develop dimers analogous to wild type enzyme. Difference lies between the Mutations at His-101 and His-271, since in the prior the values of heat stability are not altered. Whereas the last residue leads to the formation of a thermolabile protein. Recent study of structure lead to the conclusion that His-101 behave as an intermediate of catalytic base. It has been deduced that the substitution of residue of His-271 made the characteristics of the protein thermolabile. For a metal ion His-271 act as a ligand within the active site of xylose isomerase (Carl  et al.,  1990). The true structural and functional substrates of this enzyme is pentose and xylose. Only one divalent cation required per active site by xylose isomerase. The triose phosphate isomerase activity is 1000 fold faster than xylose isomerase. The activity rate of xylose isomerase is 5 molecule per active site (Colleyer  et al ., 1990).The reversible transformation of aldose to ketose is propagated by xylose isomerase. It causes the conversion into xylose and glucose and referred as reversible isomerization (Colleyer  et al ., 1990). It was founded that xylose isomerase needed the divalent cations of Mg+2, Co+2, or Mn+2 for its activity (Chen 1980). It was reported by recent studies that Fe+2 act as a stimulator for the enzyme. It was discovered the cations of Li+ do not inhibit the activity because they are monovalent, while the trivalent cations like Al+3, Fe+3 causes the decrease in activity. It has been concluded that large divalent cations like Ca+2, Ba+2, Sr+2, Hg+2 and Pb+2 hinder activity (Chen, 1980). It has been concluded that the resultant activity of Ca+2 and Al+3 can be inverted by the excess addition of Mg+2. It has been noted by the kinetic study of fast occurring equilibrium mechanisms that the enzymatic reactions are exhibited only by ternary enzyme-metal-substrate. This result was achieved by attaching single cation with substrate at active site. It was revealed by recent studies of crystal structures of enzyme xylose isomerase that two metal ions are located per active site (Rey  et al ., 2004). It has been founded by equilibrium dialysis and spectral displacement that Co+2 metal ion is attached with a xylose isomerase produced by  S. violaceoruber . It has been reported that dual Co+2 sites are detected in a monomer of xylose isomerase. With the help of Xray absorption it was revealed that the high affinity site has octahedral co-ordination with Co+2. This reaction disclosed the strong binding site of D-xylose isomerase produced by  S. albus . It has been observed by analysis that the construction of active ternary complex includes the attachment of divalent cations to active site of enzyme (Colleyer  et al.,  1990). 
 In this work we are reporting the production and characterization of xylose isomerase from  E.coli   MATERIALS AND METHODS   3.1. Chemicals    Peptone, sodium chloride (NaCl), yeast extract, magnesium chloride (MgCl2), calcium carbonate (CaCO3), cobalt chloride (CoCl2), sodium hydroxide (NaOH), hydrochloric acid (HCl), resorcinol, ferric ammonium di sulfate (FeNH4(SO4)2), ethanol, coomassie blue dye (R-250, G-250), acrylamide, bis-acrylamide, D-fructose, Monobasic sodium phosphate, Sodium acetate, glycine, Trizma, bromophenol blue, &szlig;- meracaptoethanol, ammonium per sulfate, ammonium sulfate, EMB agar, Macconkey agar, sodium carbonate, TEMED, Tris-phosphate, crystal violet, ammonium oxalate, ethanol, Potassium iodide (KI), phosphoric acid, ethyl alcohol, acetone, safranin, Hydrogen peroxide (H2O2), Di-potassium hydrogen phosphate, glucose, phenol red, Tris-Cl buffer, glycerol, Bovine serum albumin, glucose, SDS, EDTA and TRITONX100.  3.2. Equipment    Shaking incubator, sonicator, Novagen,trail mix marker:Cat.No.70980-3 range(10-225 kDa), laminar air flow chamber, hot air oven, centrifuge machine, micropipette, spectrophotometer, cuvette, Eppendorf tube, falcon tubes (15 ml) (50 ml), refrigerator and freezer.  3.3. Glassware    250 ml flasks, 500 ml flasks, 1000 ml flasks, glass slides, 1000 ml beaker, 250 ml beaker, 50 ml beaker, 250 ml beaker, pipette (1 ml) (2 ml) (5 ml), reagent bottles (500 ml) (50 ml), droppers.  3.4. Methods   3.4.1. Strains used    Sewage samples from three location were taken i.e. shahdara, janmandir and GCU Lahore.  3.4.2. Isolation  Selective media of Nutrient agar was prepared by dissolving 0.8g of nutrient broth and 2 g of agar per 100 ml of distilled water in a 250 ml flask. Petri plates were sterilized by placing in oven at 160&ordm;C for two hours. Nutrient agar was autoclaved for 15lbs/in2 for 15 minutes at 121&ordm;C. Nutrient agar was poured in Petri plates within laminar flow cabinet under aseptic conditions. And it was allowed to be cooled and solidified with half lid open. In accordance with method of serial dilution three test tubes were filled with 9 ml of distilled water and autoclaved. Afterwards, dilution of 10- 1, 10-2, and 10-3 was prepared with serial dilution method by taking water from three specified locations. With micropipette Sewage sample from three locations of 10-1, 10-2, and 10-3 dilutions respectively were delivered onto three plates. Spreading was performed then by spreader to complete the inoculation of Sewage samples. The plates were incubated at 37&ordm;C for 24 hours. Afterwards, differential media of EMB Agar was prepared and streaked with inoculating loop by the method described in confirmation test. Minimum of single colony was picked per selective plate from selective media of Nutrient agar  3.4.3. Confirmation Tests    Five confirmation tests were performed which are stated below:  3.4.3.1. EMB (Eosine Methylene Blue) Agar Test    EMB Agar was prepared according to (Benson, 2002) by dissolving 3.6g of EMB Agar per 100 ml of distilled water and was autoclaved. The green color solution was poured onto to three labeled plates. The green solution in petri plates was allowed to solidify by keeping lid partially opened. This procedure was completed within the laminar air flow cabinet. Single colony from 10-1 dilution of nutrient agar plate was picked to streak EMB Agar plates. Then the plates were sealed with paper tape and placed in incubator in inverted position. After 48 hours of incubation at 37&ordm;C, metallic sheen colonies was observed which confirm the presence of  E. coli  in the sewage samples.  3.4.3.2. Gram Staining:  In order to distinguish gram positive bacterial strain from gram negative, gram staining technique was used in accordance with Benson (1994). Single isolated colony from fresh culture was mixed with sterilized distilled water on a clean slide. The smear was prepared by drying in air and fixed by quickly passing over the flame. Crystal violet was prepared (2g crystal violet, 0.9g ammonium oxalate and 9.5ml ethanol) dissolved per100ml of distilled water. Twenty seconds were required to cover it with this solution. The smear was then washed with distilled water. Afterwards Gram&rsquo;s iodine solution was left on the smear for 1 minute. This solution included 20g Kl and 10g in 100 ml of distilled water. A single wash of decolorizing agent (47.5 ml Ethylalcohol, 50 ml acetone and 2.5 ml distilled water) was given for few seconds. Then the smear was washed with distilled water to clear the decolorizing agent. Furthermore, smear was covered for 20 seconds with safranin (10ml of 95% ethanol mixed with 0.25 g of safranin in 90ml of distilled water). The slide was washed with distilled water and dried by tissue paper and observed under a microscope.  3.4.3.3. Catalase Test:    According to Benson (1994) the test culture having thick growth was dipped in 3ml of 3% H2O2 solution by the help of a sterile glass rod. Positive catalase activity was presented by affervescence for few seconds.  2H  2  O  2  &rarr;   2H  2  O + O  2     3.4.3.4. Macconkey Agar Test:    According to Cheesbrough (1993) MacConkey agar medium was prepared (50 ml), sterilized and poured into two sterile Petri plates and allowed to solidify. The plates were inoculated with  E. coli  via sterile loop and incubated at 37&ordm;C for overnight.  3.4.3.5. Phenol Red Test:    According to Cheesbrough (1993) medium was made for the test of phenol red by dissolving 5g of K2HPO4 and 5g of peptone in 1L of distilled water. The pH was set at 7.6 and the solution was transferred to test tube. The solution was autoclaved for 15lbs/in2 for 20 minutes at 121&deg;C. The test tube contained 5ml of medium with 0.25ml of glucose. The media above was inoculated with  E.coli  strains and incubated at 37&deg;C for 48 hours. Additionally, phenol red was prepared by adding 300ml of ethanol and 18 0.1g of phenol red per 100 ml of distilled water. 5 drops of phenol red was necessary to be mixed in the medium. The positive result was presented by cherry red color.  3.5. Culture revival    Two g of agar and 0.8 g of Nutrient broth was dissolved in 100ml of distilled water. After it was autoclaved and poured. It was allowed to cool down. Nutrient agar was streaked with single colony aseptically in laminar cabinet by sterilized inoculating loop. Nutrient broth consists chemically of 1% peptone, 1% NaCl and 0.5% yeast extract. The inoculated plates were then placed in incubator at 37&ordm;C for 24 hours.  3.6. Culture preservation     3.6.1.Preparation of Glycerol Stock Solution    The quantity of Nutrient broth dissolved was 2.5 g per 100 ml of distilled water. The media was autoclaved and allowed to cool for 10 min. The fresh culture from EMB agar Plate was picked and the media was inoculated. The media having culture growth was incubated for overnight in the incubator at 37&ordm;C. Next day the media turned turbid exhibiting growth of  E.coli . Afterwards 200 &micro;l of glycerol was added in each Eppendorf tube and these tubes were autoclaved at standard conditions. Then 800 &micro;l of broth culture was added in it, vortex and stored at -20&ordm;C.  3.7. Optimized fermentation conditions    The fermentation conditions for culture growth by locally isolated  E.coli  were varied by varying media composition. The individual components of Nutrient Broth i.e. peptone, sodium chloride (NaCl) and yeast extract were altered respectively. The media was placed in shaker for 48 hours at temperature of 37&ordm;C after it was inoculated with vegetative inoculum. Vegetative inoculum was prepared by inoculating the Nutrient broth (media) with single colony of  E.coli . Then culture was placed in shaker at 200 rpm at 37&ordm;C for overnight and vegetative inoculum was made. The media turned turbid exhibiting formation of vegetative inoculum. The effect of MnSO4 by its addition in media was also determined as displayed in table 2 and 3.  3.8. Mass production    Several batches of culture were grown at the optimized conditions to get a suitable amount of cell mass. Six 250 ml flasks were initially taken used for mass 19 production of locally isolated  E.coli  strain. Out of which three were selected on the second turn. 1% xylose was also added to media as it enhances enzyme production in  E. coli  as followed by (Schellenberg  et al.,  1984). Vegetative inoculum was grown in nutrient broth having 1% xylose with colony inoculation of a streaked plate and placed in shaker at 37&ordm;C at 200 rpm for 24 hours. The six flasks contained varying concentration of individual components of nutrient broth having 1% xylose addition. Next day the autoclaved; six Medias were inoculated with 2 ml of vegetative inoculum and placed in shaker at 37&ordm;C at 200 rpm for 48 hours.  3.9. Harvesting of cells    For harvesting the cells, initially the (Optical density) O.D of six flasks of 48 hours cultures were taken.  E. coli  cultures were shifted in six 50 ml centrifuge tubes and were centrifuged at 6000 rpm for 5 minutes at 4&ordm;C and then supernatant was discarded. Tris-Cl buffer of (pH 8) was used for the suspension of cells. The pellet was kept in 15 ml falcon tube at -20&deg;C.  3.10. Cell lysis    For cell disruption several methods can be used for example sonication method, physical method or chemical method. In this case, sonication method was applied by setting its frequency to small cross sectional area. The exposure time for disruption of  E.coli  cells was 30 seconds followed next by 30 seconds interval. This cycle lasts for 30 minutes. The finishing point of sonication process was indicated by conversion to grey color of media. Again, each media culture was moved to 50 ml centrifuge tube and it was centrifuged at 12,000 rpm for 15 min at 4&ordm;C. This time supernatant was saved containing crude enzyme for which enzyme activity and total protein content was determined.  3.11. Total protein content    Furthermore, the total protein content was determined by standard Bradford&rsquo;s method. The Bradford reagent was prepared for the measurement of total protein. Preparation of Bradford reagent was as followed. For the preparation of 1L Bradford&rsquo;s reagent, 100mg Coomassie blue G-250 dye was dispersed in 50 ml 95% ethanol and 100 ml of 85% phosphoric acid was added into it. The volume was raised up to 1000ml by distilled water. The solution was filtered and placed in amber colored glass bottle in order to avoid photo- oxidation. Then standard curve was constructed as displayed in figure 3.1, for different concentrations of BSA. The total protein content was estimated for crude enzyme when 0.1 ml of sample was added in 2.5 ml of Bradford&rsquo;s reagent in a test tube. The test tube was incubated at room temperature for 5&ndash;10 minutes and then OD was measured at 590 nm 
